text: These are just some of the films and TV shows which have filmed in *Bradford City Hall* and/or the half a mile radius surrounding it in *Bradford* city centre:  *Emmerdale, Coronation Street, Monty Python's Flying Circus, Gentleman Jack, The ABC Murders, Peaky Blinders, Victoria, King Charles III, The Windsors, Gunpowder, Girlfriends, South Riding, Seaforth, Ackley Bridge, Band of Gold, A Touch of Frost, The Great Train Robbery, The Brides in the Bath, The Red Riding Trilogy, Spooks: Code 9, DCI Banks, Happy Valley, The Syndicate, Room at the Top (2012), Damon and Debbie, Utopia, Residue, The Moorside, National Treasure, Bollywood Carmen Live, Dynamo: Magician Impossible, Portillo's Hidden History of Britain, The Hairy Builder, Songs of Praise, Heston's Great British Food, Rick Stein's Food Heroes, Ramsay's Best Restaurant, Welcome to Karachi, Gold, 1920, 1920: London, Commando 3, Billy Liar, Lies We Tell, Official Secrets, Testament of Youth, Funny Cow, The Selfish Giant, Wall of Tyranny, The Damned United, Blow Dry, LA Without a Map, The Dresser, A Private Function, To Walk Invisible, Life at the Top, Room at the Top (1959)* etc etc.  *Downton Abbey* (2019) filmed in *Little Germany* and most likely used some of the same buildings in the above films and TV shows.  The most popular *Bradford* city centre locations seem to be:  1 - *Bradford City Hall* and the *Bradford Police Museum* (which is downstairs) has been used by at least 40 or 50 productions. Most of which have been in the last 10 years.  2 - *Bradford City Park* which surrounds *Bradford City Hall* (along with the *Magistrates Court* and the now demolished *Bradford Central* Police station) and usually coincides with filming inside *Bradford City Hall* in productions set in modern time periods.  3 - *Little Germany* which I'd estimate has also been used by at least 40 or 50 productions. Most notably in *Bradford Cathedral,* *The Bradford Club,* the *Bradford Playhouse* and a warehouse between Cater Street and Hick Street (which no-one ever seems to notice apart from me).   4 - *The Midland Hotel* which has been used by at least 5 productions in the last few years.   5 - *The National Science and Media Museum* which obviously mainly gets used for news productions.   6 - *The Broadway Bradford* which has been used for around 5 productions since it opened 3 years ago.  7 - *Bradford College* which has been used by at least 5 productions in the last few years.  8 - *The Alhambra Theatre.*  9 - *The Bradford Odeon* has been used by at least 5 productions since it closed in 2000. It even was one of just a few places in the country to show the 2017 *Doctor Who* Christmas special days before it appeared on TV.  10 - *The Wool Exchange.*  11 - *The Bradford Hotel* which I haven't noticed in anything recent, but appeared in a few things in the 1990's.  12 - *Bradford Interchange* which again I haven't noticed in anything recent, but appeared in a few things in the 1990's.  13 - *Bradford Crown Court* which I've only noticed in one drama, but has most likely been used in others.  Outside the city centre locations include:  1 - *Lister Park* and *Cartwright Hall* which has easily been used at least 10 times.  2 - *Haworth* and *The Bronte Parsonage Museum* which obviously mainly gets used for productions about the *Bronte Sisters.*  3 - *Valley Parade* which has been used in at least 5 drama productions (not that anyone realises), as well as all the shows about football or the *Bradford Fire.*  4 - *East Riddlesden Hall* which has been used in at least 5 productions.  5 - *Peel Park* which has been used in a few productions recently.  6 - *Undercliffe Cemetery* which has been used in at least 10 productions.  7 - *Salts Mill* and *Saltaire* which must have been used by at least 30 productions by now.  8 - *Ilkley Moor* and the *Cow and Calf Rocks* which again must have been used by at least 30 productions.  9 - *Dalton Mills* which has been used by around 20 productions.  10 - *Odsal Stadium* which has doubled for *Wembley* a few times.  11 - *Bolling Hall* which strangely only seems to have been used a few times, even though it's one of the oldest buildings in the city, is mentioned in the *Domesday Book,* and has been involved in real wars.   12 - *Keighley and Worth Valley Railway* which has been used by at least 50 productions. Maybe even as many as 100 productions.  There's no doubt many places I've forgotten about, and no doubt many films and TV shows I don't know about yet, but when I do and have got my Bradford Film Locations blog started, I'll start adding them to *IMDB* and *Wikipedia,* and I'll let the official *Bradford Film Heritage* know what's missing from their website.  We aren't the world's first *UNESCO City of Film* for no reason.

text: I'm watching all 6 seasons again with subtitles, got them at the library. I am really looking forward to this movie.  I read the book "Lady Almina and the Real Downton Abbey" for free on hoopladigital.com with my library card. It's what got me to watch the series again. It's written by the current Countess of Carnarvon at Highclere Castle. You will find many similar themes, characters, treasures and anecdotes from the real history of the place and it's residents. Lady Almina's husband discovered the tomb of King Tut, along with his hired excavator Howard Carter, and then promptly died of the Curse of Tomb Robbing. It was and maybe still is the longest running news story in British history. Lady Almina did indeed run a hospital at Highclere during the war, but she was much more involved than in the series, and became known as a great healer. I can't wait for September! I'll be so ready for the next chapters in this epic story. I may have to go all by myself so I don't miss anything by talking to a friend about it as we watch. I'm sure I'll see it more than once. Love those accents! Love all the characters. Brilliant!
